    "basmil_timeline_rrN3mU": {
      "type": "basmil-timeline",
      "blocks": {
        "block_Bp9W3R": {
          "type": "block",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Background of the Third Mithridatic War (67 B.C.)</h2><p>As tensions grew between Rome and its neighbors, the \"Poison King,\" rose to power in Pontus, ready to challenge Roman influence. The third Mithridatic War (73-63 B.C.) was his final attempt to stop Roman control. </p><p>With the help of local allies, he fought against Rome’s growing power in Asia Minor. This battle led to a fierce conflict that changed the region's future and ultimately weakened his rule. </p>"
          }
        },
        "block_aRmG4Y": {
          "type": "block",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>The Strategic Plan to Weaken Rome</h2><p>As he had an apt knowledge of poisons, he used mad honey as a hidden weapon against the Roman army. By mixing local honey with grayanotoxins, he weakened the soldiers. This clever tactic was part of his big evil plan to win over Rome and protect his kingdom.</p>"
          }
        },
        "block_a9FNYQ": {
          "type": "block",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Rome Marching Toward Pontus</h2><p>The Roman army, led by Lucius Licinius Lucullus, marched toward Pontus, unaware of Mithridates' plan. They crossed tough, unfamiliar territory, including areas producing a unique type of honey. The Roman army was still unaware of how mad honey would be the reason for their loss. </p>"
          }
        },
        "block_7Q8YJ3": {
          "type": "block",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Consuming Mad Honey</h2><p>As the Turkish army neared the mad honey, they eagerly consumed it, enjoying its sweet taste. Soon after, they began feeling disoriented and weak due to the honey’s toxic effects. Eating too much of it left them vulnerable, unable to stay alert, and easy targets for Mithridates’ planned attack.</p>"
          }
        },
        "block_iFWJ8J": {
          "type": "block",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Mad Honey Aftermath </h2><p>After consuming the poisoned honey, Roman soldiers began feeling dizzy, confused, and weak. Some were so badly affected that they became unable to continue fighting, leaving them vulnerable to Mithridates' attack. The unexpected effects of the honey severely weakened the Roman army, hindering their ability to proceed with their mission.</p>"
          }
        },
        "block_Fqa7BB": {
          "type": "block",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Surprise Attack</h2><p>Seeing the Roman army weakened by the poisoned honey, Mithridates took advantage of their disarray. He launched a swift surprise attack while the soldiers were still struggling with dizziness and weakness. The unexpected assault caught the Romans off guard, giving Mithridates the upper hand and shifting the momentum of the battle in his favor. </p>"
          }
        },
        "block_UWpWDt": {
          "type": "block",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Long Lasting Legacy </h2><p>Mithridates used mad honey to weaken the Roman soldiers, making them sick and easy to attack. This clever trick gave him an edge in battle and showed his skill at using nature to outsmart his enemies.His legacy is still alive in the history of rulers for his brutal yet brilliant strategies, which still send chills down the spine of those who study his life and reign.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
